stocks.news:
Cava Beats Earnings:

Cava (CAVA -0.79%) cleared earnings expectations, sending the stock higher.

Cava, Chipotle (CMG -0.35%) and other fast casual chains have had a tough year in the market.

But Cava ended up reporting record revenue and said it expects to continue to grow in 2026.

economy.commentary:
Consumer Confidence Rebounds:

U.S. consumer confidence has been trending lower ‚Äî but finally got a bounce in the latest report. Respondents said they're feeling better about job opportunities and inflation. Worth noting: The survey was conducted before the Supreme Court struck down President Trump's tariffs.

Trump's 401k Plan:

President Trump called for government-backed 401k plans in last night's State of the Union address.

New Tariffs in Effect:

President Trump's new global tariffs took effect Tuesday, at 10%, for the next 150 days. He had posted on Truth Social over the weekend it would be 15%, and that is still his goal. An ING analyst says Trump could just keep ordering 150 days' worth of tariffs as a new strategy.

crypto.commentary:
No Pardon for SBF:

According to reports, President Trump will not issue a pardon for Sam Bankman-Fried.

SBF was the founder of FTX, a crypto exchange that collapsed due to fraud.

Some people thought Trump may issue a pardon to SBF after Binance's founder, Changpeng Zhao, was pardoned.

real_estate.commentary:
The Bay Area continues to be a strong seller's market characterized by historically tight inventory and stable-to-rising median prices, particularly in high-demand pockets supported by AI sector growth.

Latest Real Estate News in the Bay Area:

üè° Inventory Shortages Persist: Across Silicon Valley, single-family home inventory remains down 12% year-over-year, keeping the region firmly in a seller's market with less than one month of supply in Santa Clara County.

üè° A Tale of Two Markets: A significant divergence has emerged between property types; single-family homes in Alameda County move quickly in roughly 19 days, while condominiums are sitting for an average of 51 days as their values soften.

üè° Price Performance Trends: While Santa Clara County saw a modest 3.89% year-over-year dip in median single-family prices to $1,730,051, Alameda County saw a turnaround with prices rising 2.86% to a median of $1,150,000.
